@MrLondon on #ShadThames... definitely one of my favourite streets in London... in the late 1800‚Äôs these bridges connected the old riverside buildings to the storehouses and mills, so clippers (small cargo ships) could unload their cargo such as spices, dried fruit, teas, coffee etc - this area was quite literally known as the ‚Äòlarder of London‚Äô. Over time to city moved to containers which were unloaded further east, so by the 1970‚Äôs this whole area transitioned to residential and now feature expensive apartments, cafes, bars and restaurants. But it‚Äôs still a treat to walk under these bridges and soak the history up! And it‚Äôs right next to Tower Bridge. üéâüî•üí™üèº ANNDD WE‚ÄôRE BACK! üí™üèºüî•üéâ @MrLondon checking in... finally... after having my phone stolen on #OxfordStreet last Friday whilst taking photos of the Christmas lights. ü§¶üèª‚Äç‚ôÇÔ∏èü§¶üèª‚Äç‚ôÇÔ∏è Luckily not hurt. I‚Äôve learned the hard way that this is sadly happening across our city, especially around Oxford St, Regent St, Covent Garden, Soho etc. I‚Äôm not here to be an anti-PR machine as we head into Christmas. I just want people to be aware and safe. People just need to be wise to the fact there are organised gangs on mopeds and bikes, and they know that we‚Äôre all stopping to gawp at the Christmas lights, so they come from behind on their bikes and snatch your phone and BOOM... they‚Äôre gone. üò≠ We all rely on our phones so much, so it‚Äôs worth being safe on the streets, and also taking time to check that your photos and docs are all backed up, because if you lose your memories it‚Äôs a pretty painful experience. So use things like iCloud or backup to your PC etc. üëåüèº Also think about your two-factor authentication for Instagram and have it set up to a different number than the one being stolen (theoretically)... or you will get locked out like I did. üôàü§¶üèª‚Äç‚ôÇÔ∏è I have a spare PayAsYouGo phone / SIM for this purpose now so I can get back online quicker and faster. Oh and if it happens, which I hope it won‚Äôt, call your network provider - ask a police officer if needs be - to block the SIM to the phone. üì∏ AND for photography, whether with a camera or phone, have a friend watch over you whilst you‚Äôre taking pics. I‚Äôve got so many messages from people who‚Äôve had the same thing happen. So many phones. And a few with expensive cameras. So we all need to be alert. I was the 9th person in 1 HOUR to get caught in the same spot opposite Selfridges. BE AWARE. STAY SAFE. ‚ù§Ô∏è‚ù§Ô∏è‚ù§Ô∏è___________________________________________#thisislondon #lovelondon #london #londra #londonlife #londres #uk #visitlondon #british #üá¨üáß #londonchristmas

@belleannee with art news! üñº Better late than never. @RoyalAcademyArts ‚ÄúSummer‚Äù Exhibition opens TOMORROW & marks the first time in RA‚Äôs 252 years that the Summer Exhibition has been postponed until autumn. üò± (Note that it has never been cancelled! #BlackLivesMatter | This evening we‚Äôre sharing the work of @MisanHarriman & @RonTimehin - powerful photos taken from the protests over the past week. üì∏üî•üñ§ A full set of their images will be posted to our story tonight. Thanks for sharing guys. ‚ù§Ô∏è____________________________________London is a city encompassing more than 270 nationalities and 300 languages and at these protests, people of every nationality and skin colour stood shoulder-to-shoulder in solidarity to declare that Black Lives Matter - because for centuries, they haven‚Äôt. And as recently as May 25th - when George Floyd was brutally murdered in a 21st century lynching - his life didn‚Äôt matter to those white policemen. üòî That senseless violence proved to be the straw that broke the camels back and the world has stood up and said ‚Äúenough is enough‚Äù. ü§∑üèª‚Äç‚ôÇÔ∏è It‚Äôs a beautiful thing to watch London‚Äôs community in action. People laid aside their own problems, the challenges their own nations are facing, the problems within their own cultures and families, to lift up a community in incomprehensible amounts of pain. This has been their time to be heard, understood and supported. And we can only pray that the momentum of this movement will translate into deep and wide-spread societal change, here in the UK, and all around the world. ‚ù§Ô∏èüñ§‚ù§Ô∏è____________________________________We believe that all lives should matter. But we acknowledge they don‚Äôt. There is inequality. There is persecution. There is injustice. We cannot pretend that systemic racism doesn‚Äôt exist. And we cannot ignore the first-hand experiences of our black friends and their families, and the trauma they are experiencing during this season - they‚Äôve spent years trying to forget these experiences, and now they‚Äôve come flooding back. ü§∑üèª‚Äç‚ôÇÔ∏èüíî _________This has quickly become a world-wide anti-racist movement and the conversations we‚Äôre having now have been needed for a long time. We simply need your YES & AMEN! This isn‚Äôt a competition for who‚Äôs suffering the most. We‚Äôre not forgetting that other people have needs. We‚Äôre just focusing on one group of people rightg now, and we need all your love, all your empathy & all your compassion. ‚ù§Ô∏è

@MrLondon with a little history... It‚Äôs 1968. Beatles ‚ÄúLady Madonna‚Äù is Number 1. Protests ring out around London against the Vietnam War. And RAF Veteran pilot Alan Pollock is angry at defence cuts and that his beloved RAF aren‚Äôt marking their 50th anniversary with a fly-by in London. So Alan decided to take matters into his own hands, and whilst flying from Sussex to Norfolk he fakes radio problems and taps out a message to his commanders saying he‚Äôs lost visual sight of his 3 comrades and will make his own way back. üò≥ Using just an AA map as a guide, he drops to 150ft below commercial aviation traffic, flies over Whitehall, dips his wings over the RAF Memorial in tribute, and then drops down to the Thames. Travelling at a speed of 300mph the #TowerBridge was quickly upon him and he makes a split second decision to fly THROUGH IT rather than over it, remembering at the last second he had a tail fin behind his head, which nearly catches the underside of the bridge! üò± Alan‚Äôs opinion was that it‚Äôs in the Air Force‚Äôs blood to celebrate in the air - not on the ground. Parades were not befitting in his view. ü§∑üèª‚Äç‚ôÇÔ∏èü§£ A cyclist fell off his bike and tore his trousers. Thankfully no-one was hurt. Alan called his wife‚Äôs mother and gave them a heads up - ‚Äúthere might be a bit of trouble - but not to worry‚Äù. He said. Alan after receiving widespread support from across the RAF was spared an official court martial and instead ‚Äúretired on medical grounds‚Äù, probably to deny him the chance to complain about the defence cuts. Looking back at 82 Alan said he had no regrets. ‚ò∫Ô∏èü§∑üèª‚Äç‚ôÇÔ∏èü§£______________________________________________#thisislondon #lovelondon #london #londra #londonlife #londres #uk #visitlondon #british #üá¨üáß #raf #royalairforce #londonhistory üì∏ Artist depiction by @Gary.Eason / @flight.artworks in consultation with the pilot.

#VEDAY75 | Victory in Europe Day, generally known as VE Day or V-E Day, is a day celebrating the formal acceptance by the Allies of World War II of Nazi Germany's unconditional surrender of its armed forces on Tuesday, 8 May 1945, marking the end of World War II in Europe. Years of carnage and destruction had come to an end and millions of people took to the streets and pubs to celebrate peace, mourn their loved ones and to hope for the future. ‚ù§Ô∏è_______________________________________These images serve as a reminder of not only of the sacrifices of our ancestors and grand parents, but of a time when the country united to rebuild the nation. üí™üèº The country is urged to remember, lest we forget, and draw on the same spirit of national endeavour as we work together through the present coronavirus crisis. üôèüèº‚ù§Ô∏èüôèüèº_______________________________________#WinstonChurchill said on this day 75 years ago... ‚ÄúEveryone has tried. @MrLondon checking in for #WorldMentalHealthDay... today is all about suicide prevention and awareness. Did you know someone dies from suicide every 40 seconds? ü§∑üèª‚Äç‚ôÇÔ∏è That‚Äôs almost 800,000 people lost every year, and that‚Äôs why we need to talk about it more. üôèüèº I‚Äôve personally experienced depression. And I‚Äôve battled with anxiety for a couple of years. I‚Äôve also had panic attacks that have been debilitating. Growing up I would never have talked about it, let alone on Instagram - I would have always tried to ‚Äúman up‚Äù. ü§∑üèª‚Äç‚ôÇÔ∏è But you know what? I‚Äôm not ashamed and I‚Äôm very comfortable talking about it. In fact I love talking about it because if my story can help just ONE person to talk to a friend, a family member, or even a colleague or classmate, then it will have been worth it. üí™üèº If you‚Äôre struggling, talk to someone. Do it tonight. Don‚Äôt suffer in silence you can find hope. You can break through. D-Day | #HMSBelfast | On this day, 75 year ago, 156,000 allied troops landed on the beaches of occupied #Normandy. HMS Belfast is one of only 3 bombardment vessels to survive. Casualties were treated on-board and they spent 33 days supporting the landings, firing over 4,000 6-inch and 1,000 4-inch shells. This was the last time she fired her guns in World War II. The gallant actions of British, US & Commonwealth forces secured a bridgehead that enabled the liberation of Europe from Nazi domination. Called #OperationOverlord, today it is more usually referred to as D-Day. The forces landed on five beaches, with parachute and special forces dropped in before the main assault.D-Day was, and remains now, the largest combined land, sea and air operation in history. By the end of the 6th of June 1944, 10,000 allied casualties had been taken. The relative stability that we have enjoyed since then is as a direct result of their sacrifice, as well of all those gave their lives to fight the forces of fascism.At the going down of the sun, and in the morning, we will remember them. // #DDay #DDay75 #WW2 #WorldWar2 #remember #remembrance #wewillrememberthem #lestweforget #respect #veterans #thisislondon @imperialwarmuseums @britisharmy üì∏ @mrlondon

Arts & Culture editor @belleannee popping in with a weekend idea for you: @LeightonHouseMuseum is the former home of Lord Leighton, a celebrated British artist from the Victorian era. His is the only purpose-built studio-house open to the public in the UK and from the outside you‚Äôd never believe what the inside holds! The museum gives an insight into the wealth, taste and status of a successful and flamboyant artist, Royal Academician and founder of the Holland Park Circle, lived 130+ years ago. The strict no üö´üì∑ rule forces you to be in the moment and take it all in.... as he undoubtedly lived his life. (And no rules were broken... Permission for these pics was graciously provided by Leighton House). Open 9-5:30 daily, closed Tuesdays. Check the website for a ton of special events they host including drink + draw in the studio, family events and lates. // #thisislondon #londonart

Arts editor @belleannee here checking in with a bit of architecture & design for your arts and culture this weekend. This is @spencer.house, the sumptuously designed and impeccably preserved 18th-century residence built by the first #EarlOfSpencer, an ancestor of the late #PrincessDiana. See, way back when, when a noble title was bestowed upon you, the expectation of a solid social schedule was also bestowed. What else would a good noble Earl do besides build the most ambitious example of architecture and design of his day to host all those fabulous parties? Even back then (built 1756 -1766) the house was immediately hailed as one of the finest examples of its type and ‚Äúsubtle‚Äù wasn‚Äôt in the designers vocabulary. Lucky for us it has survived 250 years intact and is available for tours (as well as private hire if you want to be nobility for the day). ü§© // #thisislondon #london #londonart || üì∏ All photos by the lovely @skyeoneill - thank you! ‚ù§Ô∏èüôèüèº

@MrLondon with a LEGAL photo taken from a helicopter above #TowerBridge. For anyone caught up in the #Gatwick Drone nightmare - we‚Äôre so sorry that you‚Äôve suffered. üòï‚ù§Ô∏è If we as a nation haven‚Äôt got a technical answer to triangulating drones - God help us. We were triangulating radio transmitters in the first and second world wars. Now we have satellites in the sky and have put a man on the moon, why we can‚Äôt deal with these drones is beyond me. ü§∑üèº‚Äç‚ôÇÔ∏è It‚Äôs a scary vulnerability that our transport hubs can be broken so easily. What I will say is that it‚Äôs about time the CAA started to make examples of the people flouting the laws. And that includes instagrammers who think it‚Äôs cool to fly above the 400ft ceiling. Its not cool. It‚Äôs unbelievably stupid. And it‚Äôs no use the CAA re-publishing guidelines and rules if you don‚Äôt enforce them. People are regularly flying drones above Tower Bridge at the same height I was flying in this helicopter. You only have to look at the recent helicopter crash in Leicester to see what happens when a helicopter comes down. We publish the work of @jasonhawkes regularly, another helicopter aerial specialist photographer. There are ways to shoot these type of photos legally and professionally. But people trying to push the limits for the sake of the ‚Äògram are putting lives at risk and they are going to regret the day they take down a helicopter or plane taking off from any of the 3 neighbouring airports. It‚Äôs going to happen, eventually. About time CAA got a grip. üí•üëäüèºüí• // #thisislondon #london #drones

Arts & Culture editor @Belleannee checking in with a timely nudge: There is lots to know about global warming but sometimes it can be hard to put scientific data into something we can visualize. Enter artists Olafur Eliasson and Minil Rosing who have installed an outdoor sculpture at @Tate Modern and Bloomberg‚Äôs European HQ both in #London. It‚Äôs made of huge chunks of glacier ice from the Greenland ice sheet that had broken away and were melting into the ocean. It is an interactive exhibit intended to make us see and feel what we only read about or hear politicians arguing about. Get there quickly, touch it. Feel it. Listen to it. See it. Watch it melt. The exhibit will be there until the ice melts away. #londonart #icewatchlondon || üì∏ Images from @studioolafureliasson & @justin_sutcliffe üôèüèº

@MrLondon checking in. I‚Äôm contemplating #ArmisticeDay as our day of remembrance draws to a close, marking 100 years since the end of World War One. My heart is full of gratitude for those that fought for the freedom I have today, especially my forefathers. Pic 1 is my Great Grandad who fought in WW1. He was blown up in France and suffered serious shrapnel wounds. An angelic soldier and comrade pulled him off the battlefield, and after being repatriated to England, he survived his injuries and went onto marry and have 4 children. He‚Äôd enlisted underage at 17. Pic number 2 is my Grandad who was taken as a prisoner of war when Singapore fell in 1942. He was caught up in the Thai/Burma railway construction known as the Death Railway, designed to take Japanese Imperial Army troops and supplies from Bangkok to Burma. One man died for every railway sleeper laid. üòî The 3rd pic is me. 4 generations on. Walking in #RegentsPark without any fear. Today I can write this whilst eating a roast dinner surrounded by friends. Whatever may trouble me now seems to pale into insignificance. Tonight I will be watching ‚ÄúThe Railway Man‚Äù - it‚Äôs all about the aforementioned PoW railway and stars Colin Firth & Nicole Kidman. It‚Äôs my way of reflecting upon my family‚Äôs own sacrifices, at a time when the entire nation reflects on many conflicts, many lives lost, many sacrifices made. My heart is full of gratitude and my prayers are that those in modern day conflict would know peace. Lots of love to everyone. #LestWeForget üá¨üáß‚ù§Ô∏èüá¨üáß // #thisislondon #london #rememberanceday #ww1 #ww2

A slice of history... #GuyFawkes night or ‚ÄúBonfire Night‚Äù is when Brits gather under firework lit skies to watch dummies burn on bonfires! üî• Why?! ü§∑üèº‚Äç‚ôÇÔ∏è It‚Äôs actually the anniversary of an attempt to blow up the #HousesOfParliament - known as the Gunpowder Plot. The dummies - or Guy - refer to Guy Fawkes who was part of the plot. Back in 1605 the plan was to blow up King James I and his government! England was Protestant. The plotters were Catholic. 36 barrels of explosive gunpowder were hidden in the cellars of parliament, but the king‚Äôs supporters got hold of a letter warning a friend to stay away from the Houses of Parliament on the 5th November. The plotters were tumbled and subsequently executed. The plot was immortalised in a nursery rhyme ‚ÄúRemember, remember, the fifth of November, gunpowder, treason and plot...‚Äù // Have a wonderful evening everyone! üì∏ @tmnikonian üî• // #thisislondon #london #bonfirenight #fireworks üá¨üáß‚ù§Ô∏èüá¨üáß

Arts & Culture editor @belleannee here with two great #London art stories for you. The first is that of @theunitlondon, a contemporary art gallery in the heart of #Mayfair run by Joe Kennedy and Jonathan Burt. Joe and Johnathan met in secondary school in West London and are now twentysomethings pushing and kicking the artworld into the 21st century. From how they find artists as well as buyers (social media) to the super warm welcome that greets you when you visit their gallery, the partners pride themselves on doing things a new way. They are just packing up 21st Century Women, a show curated by and featuring top female movers in the art world including @anne_morris_studio (this is the second London story I have for you). Anne is a British artist whose multimedia creations are are much loved by brands, collectors and critics. She is an illustrator, a sculpture, a painter‚Ä¶. a you name it. And these tall sculptures are my new favourites. Don‚Äôt you want to stare and them and touch them and play with them? Is there any better art than one that makes you desperate to feel it? Thank you to @theunitlondon for the shot of @anne_morris_studio‚Äôs studio and if you have a chance to pop into Unit today you will catch the last day of the 21 Century Women exhibit. Otherwise keep an eye on their IG account for what is coming next. // #thisislondon #london #londonart #unitlondon

Solidarity is a big part of #LondonFromHome:‚Å£"I'm used to walking across the metropolis along linear roads, crossing zones to communicate with those who share my life. Meandering my way through the crowds of tourists taking pictures of Big Ben and Westminster Abbey and I occasionally get bellowed 'excuse me, can you take a picture of me?‚Äô And of course I can spare a few seconds on their request. But now the feeling of walking around London in near silence is still a very strange feeling. ‚†Ä‚Å£‚†Ä‚Å£Living in an apartment complex, you never really get attached to people as we all hold our guard up. Yet now being unable to travel freely most of us have turned to our neighbours, hurriedly discarding the unspoken agreement to disregard each other. I found a note slipped under the door a day before the lockdown: "Dear neighbour, if you have fallen ill and/or need any help with shopping, cooking or having medicine during self-isolation, please send us a call." I told my friends, and as the days went by, several of them mentioned receiving similar messages. People at my floor were unexpectedly able to hand their mobile number out to total strangers. It provoked an unexpected thrill; a sense of neighbourly culture, a way outside our immediate circle to show compassion.‚†Ä‚Å£‚†Ä‚Å£As haven't seen my parents or my sisters family for 2 months video calling helps a lot and boosts my morale when thoughts get rough. For now, I have my neighbours who are my family during this tough time." üì∏xüìù by @krixhhna

The news has been difficult to watch for many months now but more so over the last few days. As a medic that's currently on maternity leave, I feel like I'm watching from the sidelines as my colleagues battle on. And from first-hand stories from friends on the frontline, I can tell that staff are at breaking point.-Today there are more people in hospital with COVID in England than EVER BEFORE. Speaking up about this isn't trying to stir panic, it's trying to raise awareness about what things are like. And I get that "pandemic-fatigue" is real and people are tired, but so are NHS staff. More and more people are dying and hospitals are struggling. So please remember to continue to take things seriously and continue following the rules.-Today's shot comes from @banubilecen and is also a reminder that there's a full moon tonight, the final one of 2020, called the Cold Moon. Happy weekend team! Sun's out but it's still freezing outside so we're staying all snuggled up at home today. We've been swaddling our little one using the @merinokids newborn cocooi baby wrap and I wanted to talk about safe swaddling today!-We love this wrap because the Merino fabric works to regulate body temperature, it's light, soft to touch, non-itchy, hypo-allergenic and naturally odour-releasing! (Ad - PR product @babasocialuk).-Follow these seven safe and hip-friendly swaddling tips:-1. Swaddle your baby using thin, breathable materials, like the cocooi wrap, and don‚Äôt over layer them.-2. Don‚Äôt swaddle your baby above their shoulders.-3. Wrap your baby firmly but gently (not too tightly). Tight swaddling that stops your baby's hips and knees moving freely is not recommended. Swaddling your baby too tightly might cause hip dysplasia, which is where the hip does not form correctly.-4. Make sure your baby is able to move their hips and knees freely to kick. Your baby‚Äôs legs should be able to fall into a natural position (like frog-legs üê∏).-5. Always put your baby to sleep on their back. Never put a swaddled baby to sleep on their front or side.-6. Check your baby‚Äôs temperature to make sure they don‚Äôt get too hot or overheat. Check they‚Äôre wearing suitable clothes for the weather too.-7. If someone else looks after your baby, make sure they also know about safe sleeping advice and how to swaddle safely. Take your time to show them and explain the tips above!-Tag someone who would love this and send it to anyone who might find it useful!-

Good morning team, happy weekend and happy #worldmentalhealthday2020 ‚ù§Ô∏è Sharing this beautiful, autumnal shot of St. James Park by @arinainlondonland, with these gorgeous reflections on the water, to share my own reflections today.-This year's theme is 'mental health for all'. I think that's so fitting, for what we've all been going through, and continue to go through. The months of lockdown and loss have had a huge impact on us all, and prioritising mental health has never been more important than it is now. Mental health problems affect around one in four people in any given year, so it's so important that we continue to talk about them. They range from common problems, such as depression and anxiety, to rarer problems such as schizophrenia and bipolar disorder. And actually, we all need to take care of our mental health and wellbeing whether we have a mental health problem or not.-@mindcharity are encouraging us to do one thing better today and have some great tips on practical steps you can take to improve and maintain your wellbeing including making time for yourself üïí, building positive relationships üë´ and getting active ü§∏. Another empty London, this time of the gorgeous Tower Bridge which probably hasn't opened to any large boats in months! üòØ Thanks @andresbalcazar_ for this stunner! üì∏-Today I wanted to talk about something I've been thinking about a lot: mental health and how important it is to be kind to each other. Especially when we're going through a period in our lives like this, which has never happened to any of us before. Everyone's fighting their own battles and we need to remember that it might not be obvious. Think before you speak and consider, is what I'm about to say true, helpful, necessary and above all, kind? I read somewhere today: be sure to taste your words before you spit them out, which is so powerful. ‚ù§Ô∏è-At a time like this, it's ok not to be super productive. It's ok if you're not learning a new skill or developing in another way. It's even ok if you feel like you're not being the sort of friend that you normally want to be. I come home on some days after work and crash for the evening by 8pm! We're all dealing with different things and taking it a day at a time. If you're feeling like things are getting too much - please remember that there is so much support out there. As a doctor currently in GP, I speak to people about their mental health on a daily basis, and it's been a lot worse over the last few months due to covid-19. So please carry on talking to people around you about how you're feeling, share with others, and speak to your GP too if you need to! Just a few thoughts there for hump day! ‚ù§Ô∏è-#prettycitylondon #thisislondon #toplondonphoto #prettylittlelondon #cntraveler #travelerinlondon #iamatraveler #mytinyatlas #ww #myoklstyle #visitlondon #visitbritain #visitengland #lovegreatbritain #mydarlinglondon #forbestravelguide #passionpassport #thatsdarling #bbcbritain #living_europe #timeoutlondon #culturetrip_ldn #hello_worldpics #guardiantravelsnaps #beautifuldestinations #suitcasetravels #bbctravel #topeuropephoto-

Let's talk about wearing masks and gloves in public. üß§üò∑-I've lost count of the number of people I see on a daily basis on my drive to and from work being out and about wearing masks and gloves. I get it - they make people feel safe. But are we using these in the right way? I've seen people wearing masks and gloves when driving on their own. I've seen people wearing gloves and holding their phones to their ears, chatting away. I've seen someone pull off a glove that he was wearing, with his teeth because his other hand was full. There is a lot of misinformation out there. Here's some things I've wanted to clarify:-üëÄ Most of the masks out there don't cover your eyes so there's no protection from getting the virus that way.-üß§ Wearing gloves protects your hands but then touching other things (phone, wallet, keys, your face, etc) with those gloves just transfers germs onto these things! You might as well not wear gloves in the first place. It also makes you less likely to wash your hands as often!-üò∑ Most masks aren't made to act as a filter for the virus. There are gaps around the sides so you can easily be sucking in air from these gaps. Just blow out when wearing a mask, and see where you feel the air on your face - those are all gaps! Some people argue that it's still more protection than nothing but it's worrying if people use these as a false reassurance.-‚ùå Taking masks and gloves off. Limit the contact you make with the outside of the mask or gloves. There's a potential that the outside is covered with germs. Discard appropriately into a bin and wash your hands afterwards!-A lot of this may seem like common knowledge but you'll be surprised at what I saw on the way home from work today. So I wanted to put it into writing. Please share with friends, to stories, etc and tag others too!-Thanks for the fab shot as always by @sarashakeel üì∏-

The conversations with families of patients suffering from covid-19 are the hardest. I had a patient this week who had to be isolated in the hospital, like many others, and so his family couldn't visit him. He was deteriorating. His son called the phone in A&E and I picked up. That his mum was waiting for her husband at home, and that she had left his dinner out on the table for him, so hurry up and come home so it doesn't go cold.-I just about kept it together. üíî Sending out my love to all those families with loved ones in hospital right now, stay strong.-#doctor #storiesfromthefrontline #frontline #nhs #nhsdoctor ##allwhatsbeautiful #underthefloralspell #englishgarden #gardeninspiration #urbangreen #flowerstagram #flowersofinstagram #flower_daily #gardening #gardendesign #colorcolourlovers #flowersmakemehappy #springinlondon #visitlondon #thisislondon #london #covid19 #covid

How's it going, London? üëã-For those of you that follow along on my stories, you may know that I split my work life over paediatrics for half the week and GP for the other half. It's a unique position to be in over this covid-19 crisis, because I'm working in the hospital and in the community.-I've been in paediatric A&E over the last few weeks and I've noticed a massive drop in the number of kids coming in. Maybe parents are managing minor illnesses on their own, which is great. But I've also seen a rise in the number of children coming in late - and therefore they are more unwell when they get to us and they're having to go to paediatric ICU for simple conditions that we could have managed easily if they'd come to us earlier. It seems that parents are terrified of coming to the hospital due to coronavirus but please remember, the paediatric A&E departments are open and safe for you to come to if you need it. Please come earlier rather than later if you are worried and if your child has symptoms of ANY illness.-Please share this message as far as you can because it will help get the message out. We've never seen this department this quiet before and it's worrying! Thank you as always ‚ù§Ô∏è-#doctor #doctorlife #paediatrics #emergency #emergencydepartment #nhs #nhsworker #nhsdoctor #corona #covid19 #coronavirus #coronalondon #LondonCity #london #londonlive #londonlife #londoner #thisislondon #london_only #londontown #igerslondon #london4all #uk

Telephone consultations in the crisis üìû‚ö†-Most of the GP practices in my local area have switched to telephone consultations. For some, more experienced GPs, that transition has been smoother than for others. I'm still training and I've not had much practice with diagnosing a patient without seeing them or examining them. But due to the coronavirus crisis, we've been left with no choice, thrown into the deep end, all to avoid patients coming in and spreading this virus to the most vulnerable.-Which brings me onto what I had to do today. I generated a list of every patient, over the age of 90, registered to our practice. These are amongst some of the most vulnerable people in our population. I was given the task of calling them and discussing end of life care decisions, in light of the risks they are facing from this virus. Can you imagine how difficult conversations like that are, over the phone, without being able to see the patient's reaction or hold their hand? Can you imagine how scary it would be to talk about dying, especially at a time like this? It was difficult. I talked to each patient about the virus and asked if they had any questions initially. I checked that they were all staying inside and limiting contact from the outside world. I checked if they had thought about what they wanted to happen to them, if they were to become unwell. I asked if they had thought about where they would like to be treated, if they would like to go into hospital or not, and if things got so bad, would they want to be resuscitated, knowing that the chances of survival would be tiny. After working through the list of patients, one after the other, answering their questions and their family's worries, I stopped. I realised I was shattered, and emotionally drained. None of this is what we've planned for, but it's the reality. And the patients were grateful to have these discussions in advance, to ensure their wishes were respected, which is ultimately what's most important ‚ù§Ô∏è-Hoping that sharing my experiences during this pandemic is insightful and again, please stay home to protect our most vulnerable. ‚ù§Ô∏è-#doctor #nhs #gp #juniordoctor #covid19 #coronavirus

Coronavirus and mental health üß†-I've been getting a lot of questions on the impact of social distancing on mental health. It is difficult, facing the prospect of staying at home and avoiding other people and I know a lot of people will feel anxious about the virus in general, but there are things that you can do to help.-TAKE CARE OF YOUR MENTAL HEALTH:1. Don't keep re-reading the same advice if it's making you feel anxious. Let others know you are struggling. Breathing exercises can help you feel more in control.2. If you're anxious about washing your hands, set a limit for 20 seconds and then stop. Plan to do something after you have washed your hands, to distract yourself.3. Keep in touch! Video chat, phone calls, text. Make plans to watch a show/read a book separately and then you can discuss this when you speak next!4. Listen to a chatty radio station or a podcast if your home feels too quiet.5. Plan how you're going to spend your time if this is something you would find helpful.6. Eat well, try to keep active with at-home workouts (including cleaning your house, dancing to music, going up and down the stairs), and stay hydrated.7. Go out into your garden if you can, spend time with the windows open, look out at the sky/birds/other animals. Let as much natural light in as you can.8. Keep your mind occupied - books, magazines, films, podcasts, puzzles... There are also ebooks and audiobooks available!-Hope this is helpful, I'll share other useful resources on my stories as always! Please share this with anyone you think might find it helpful and feel free to share it to your stories too! #ad | What do you do to feel more human again? You guys know how much I champion looking after your mental health and today I wanted to talk about taking time out to unwind. We're all on the go, all the time, especially in London, and sometimes we can forget the importance of stopping and taking the time to breathe. Connecting with nature can help with that and for me, that's as simple as sitting in a warm bathtub, closing my eyes and listening to the birds sing outside as the sun starts to set after another long day. Close your eyes - can you picture that feeling too?-@palmoliveuk have products inspired by nature that can help you feel more human again and I've loved using this in the shower for the last few months. Try it for yourself and #FeelMoreHuman ‚ù§Ô∏è #LittleBitofNature-

We checked out Carnaby Street which is looking incredible with their new Project Zero, ocean-themed Christmas lights this year!-Prepare to be immersed into a theatrical underwater scene, there's a floating kelp forest, bright, pink coral and the deep, blue sea! It's all made sustainably, using repurposed fishing netting, over 500m of post-use bubbled wrap and over 1,500 recycled plastic bottles! Over 100L of water-based, eco-friendly, vegan paint has been used for this world-first installation too! And the power used for the lights is 100% renewably sourced too!-The message is simple: One Ocean One Planet, highlighting the urgent need to protect and restore the ocean and the damaging effects of climate change! Tag everyone who would love to see this!-

Happy Monday! Here's the beautiful Kyoto garden in Holland Park, which is one of my most favourite parks in London! For dessert we tried the vegan option - the coconut malabi and the Halva parfait which is a layered chocolate cake with tahini and salted caramel mousse coated in chocolate ganache! üëå-Overall, highly recommend checking this place out. Testing 123

#ad | We're always going on about the nutritional value of our food but what we learnt this bank holiday weekend is that many of the nutrients break down with exposure to indoor lights like those at the supermarket and in your own home. The @lightdamageisreal campaign showed us that light goes through the translucent packaging that milk comes in, breaking down nutrients like vitamins A, B2 and D3 üò± We couldn't believe that this also changes the appearance, freshness and taste of milk!-The #lightdamageisreal pop up in Notting Hill gives you a chance to shop in the dark with night goggles (which is how you'd have to shop if you wanted to keep your food protected from the light) and you'll be able to learn about Noluma that certifies light-protected packaging so that you know you've got the highest level of protection for your products! Check them out until Thursday and find out more by clicking the link in our bio!-

T U L I P S üå∑-One thing we've noticed about Chicago is that there are tulips everywhere. Each year in late October or early November, tens of thousands of tulip bulbs are planted in the Michigan Avenue area from Oak Street to Roosevelt Road.-In early April, the flowers start opening up, and my mid-May it looks like a van Gogh masterpiece everywhere you look!-We had two amazing nights with @thestclairhotel in the heart of downtown Chicago, in the midst of the tulips, and in such close proximity to the tourist attractions (even the wallpaper in our room told us the bean wasn't too far away üòâ).-Stay tuned to see what else we got up to! #exploringlondonexplorechicago-

S T. C L A I R üá∫üá≤-At the start of our Chicago trip, we were lucky enough to stay right next to the Magnificent Mile, Michigan Avenue, which is Chicago‚Äôs premier commercial district. We stayed with @thestclairhotel which is a new hotel, one block away from the bustling area and we couldn't recommend it enough! Such a comfortable stay and the staff were all so lovely! We were literally on the doorstep of the shops, fashion outlets and restaurants, as well as landmarks like the historic Water Tower, the 100-story John Hancock Tower and the famous Millennium Park. Swipe to see a very wet-looking, candy-floss coloured bean and more skyscrapers! #exploringlondonexplorechicago-|| Complimentary Stay ||-

L A K E M I C H I G A N üåä-Chicago, on Lake Michigan in Illinois, is one of the largest cities in the U.S. Its skyline is filled with skyscrapers and it's world-renowned for its museums, and its damn good food, including the iconic Chicago Deep Dish Pizza üçï-Seeing the skyscrapers next to the lake (which may as well be an ocean considering its size and its own beaches!) was surreal and so stunning! #ad | Talking about mental health is something that's really important. Being a doctor and working in an inner-London GP surgery, I've seen a huge range of mental health problems firsthand, from depression to anxiety to post-traumatic stress disorder. And it's not just the mental burden, there are real physical effects on a person's appetite, weight, sleep and overall day to day life. It's something that's not openly spoken about and a lot of my patients find it difficult to open up about it. Personally, I find the most relief from talking to my husband when I'm feeling particularly down or stressed and I encourage him to do the same, especially as men are a lot more likely to keep their emotions to themselves. But sometimes you may feel that you can't talk to family or friends and that's also ok - there are still other places and people that can help.-That's why we've partnered with #CroydonTalkingTherapies which is a free and confidential mental health service for adults, if you live in London and are registered with a Croydon GP. They can provide support for a wide variety of mental health problems and offer therapies that range from online sessions and group sessions, to one to one therapy sessions with counsellors. It's so important to raise awareness about these #NHS services that are available when you need extra help and I'm so proud to use my platform to do so. Search for Croydon Talking Therapies to find out more or click the link in our bio! https://bit.ly/2FoUSS6-And if this is something you think you'd benefit from but don't live in Croydon, do speak to your GP about how you're feeling and they can point you to the local services available to you!-Let's talk more openly about mental well-being and help reduce the stigma! @nhsenglandldn‚ù§Ô∏è

AD | So back to London, let's talk about healthy eating, being more sustainable and wasting less food. You guys know we try and have as much vegan food in our diet as possible, but did you know that if everyone in London went meat free for just ONE DAY a week, we could reduce harmful greenhouse gases in the UK by 450,000 tonnes a year - that's the same as taking 1700 cars off the road! Did you also know that every year Londoners throw away 910,000 tones of food from our homes alone, and a lot of us still don't use food recycling caddies, mixing food waste with general household waste which ends up contributing to methane production in landfill sites.-So we've teamed up with @smallchangebigdifference to ask you guys to do just that - make a #smallchange to your everyday life and be part of the #bigdifference! We've moved our caddy to the kitchen and use our compostable bags so that our food waste from when we're cooking at home can all be composted ‚úîÔ∏è @smallchangelondon @islingtonlife-They have great tips on their page like the ones we've shared here, check them out and tag everyone to tell them about this great initiative too! #smallchangebigdifference ‚ôªÔ∏è #smallchangelondon #eatlessmeat #useyourcaddy #foodnotrubbish | #ad-

üá≤üá¶ H E A R T üá≤üá¶Our last Morocco post is dedicated to our driver and tour guide Hamid @corazondemarruecos ‚ô•Ô∏è Corazon de Marruecos means Heart of Morocco in Spanish and we definitely felt that we experienced that on this trip. Hamid was born and raised in the Sahara desert and has been doing these tour guides since he was 20 years old, showing his country to people from all over the world. He has learnt different languages simply by being around tourists. He was so kind and patient with us this entire trip, waiting for us to get the right pictures and taking us to the best places that weren't even on our list, as well as making sure we got to see everything we set out to. And our car was absolutely fabulous, such a luxury to be driven around in a 4 x 4 across Morocco's varied landscapes from deserts to mountains!-If you guys ever want to do a trip like ours, where we visited 7 cities/towns in 8 days, the only way to do it is by driving. Some people drive on their own but seeing the tiny roads inside the cities and the bends along the cliffsides in the mountains, we're so glad we left it to the professionals. Hamid drove for 10 hours on our longest day and still had a smile on his face at the end of it üôà He was also always on time which made our life so much easier!-When we left, we felt like we were a little family and it definitely feels like we've left a part of our hearts in Morocco. We hope that you've all enjoyed our journey as much as we have enjoyed sharing it, and hope it inspires some of you to visit this beautiful country one day. I'm in the process of writing out a detailed blog of our entire itinerary for those of you that have asked, so I'll share that once it's finished ‚ô•Ô∏è-|| Discounted excursion ||

üá≤üá¶ B A H I A A N D B Y E üá≤üá¶We went and visited the famous Bahia palace just before we said goodbye to Morocco and our incredible riad @riadtibibt üïäÔ∏è-The Bahia Palace, meaning brilliance in Arabic, is one of the best-preserved historical sites in Marrakech. Built between 1866 and 1867 by Si Moussa, this sprawling palace is set over two acres and features 150 rooms! Each of the rooms are decorated in truly elegant Moroccan style with carved stucco and cedarwood, impressive zellig fireplaces as well as a large and small riad surrounded by citrus trees!-It was a wonderful way to end our Moroccan trip of a lifetime and we said goodbye to our stunning riad with one final serving of Moroccan tea (we had several cups every single day and can't tell you how much we'll miss this!)-Tag everyone who would love to go here!-

üá≤üá¶ M A J O R E L L E üá≤üá¶The Jardin Majorelle in Marrakech is one of the most visited sites in Morocco so we had to pay a visit on our last day. It took French painter Jacques Majorelle forty years of passion and dedication to create this enchanting, botanical garden which is two and a half acres big!-We loved the buildings here and their Moorish charm, with a hint of Art Deco, and they were painted in amazingly vibrant primary colours üíôüíõ The villa houses the Islamic Art Museum of Marrakech, the Berber Museum and famously the Musee Yves Saint Laurent!-Travelling with @corazondemarruecos üöô Tag everyone who would love this!-

üá≤üá¶ M A R R A K E C H üá≤üá¶Our last night. We can't quite explain how incredible this trip has been and how amazing it's been interacting with you all and sharing our journey! We left Casablanca after visiting the mosque and drove down to Marrakech, where this epic road trip began 8 days previously.-Our riad was another stunner: @riadtibibt which means the house of birds and it was incredible, with the most eclectic collection of decor and something new to find around every corner. We hadn't stayed in anywhere like this and we loved exploring the different floors, the range of books and other bits and bobs! Our room was the largest one in the riad, the house within the house, and again, it was decorated outrageously fabulously üòÇüëå-We had a few more places to see in Marrakech before we flew home, post to come! Tag everyone who would love this!-|| Complimentary Stay ||-

üá≤üá¶ H A S A N I I üá≤üá¶A post dedicated to the beauty of the largest mosque in Africa üôè There is no way to describe this place except to call it grand and we were blown away by the intricacy and elegance of the decor inside.-We had a guided English tour and walked on beautiful red carpets barefoot and then made our way down to where worshippers cleanse themselves before prayer. Such a beautiful place!-Tag everyone who would love to see this!-

üá≤üá¶ C A S A B L A N C A üá≤üá¶Yesterday our Instagram broke and wouldn't let me upload anything (did the same thing happen to any of you guys?!)-Anyways, if you've been following our trip on a map, you may realise that our roadtrip of Morocco is coming to an end as we head back down to Marrakech to complete a full circle! We headed from Chefchaoeun with our driver @corazondemarruecos to the capital city Rabat and then arrived late evening to the city of Casablanca, which is home to the largest mosque in Africa, Hasan II. We couldn't believe our luck when we realised our hotel room looked straight out onto it!-We had been told to check out the night life in Casablanca, so we headed to the Sky 28 bar and captured this insane view! As we made our way back to the hotel (at 2am!) I found a deserted road with a row of palm trees and had to get a picture (despite almost falling asleep) and then just before we got to our hotel, we saw the mosque again, against the night sky, and managed to capture a picture with the stars! üåüüôè (SWIPE üëâ)-We were so excited to go and see the inside of the mosque the following morning - pictures to come! Tag everyone who would love to see these!-

üá≤üá¶ D J E L L A B A üá≤üá¶The djellaba is a loose-fitting unisex outer robe which originates from Morocco. The word literally means attractive. They are traditionally made of wool in different shapes and colours and have the characteristic pointed hood which is supposed to match the traditional babouche pointed slippers. It also protects the wearer from the sun and sand storms as well as act as a pocket to fit bread or groceries!-We had to get ourselves the traditional wool djellabas which were handmade by the women in the surrounding mountains and got the Chefchaoeun colour! We then stumbled across some peacocks and had an impromptu photoshoot (swipe) and also found the most incredible scent shop with solid perfumes that make Lush look like an imposter üòÇ-Finally as we were leaving Chefchaoeun and our wonderful hosts @casameryemchefchaouen, some of the market sellers asked for a picture as they saw me snapping away. They came up with their own pose and swipe to the last picture to see the final result! üòÇ I love Moroccan people! üá≤üá¶-Tag everyone who would love this!-

üá≤üá¶ C H E F C H A O U E N üá≤üá¶From Fes we headed to the blue pearl of Morocco, Chefchaoeun, which is in the northwest of Morocco in the Rif mountains. This place is a striking because of it's incredible blue-washed buildings which is said to symbolise the sky and the heaven üíô We stayed in @casameryemchefchaouen which was a very traditional apartment in the heart of the old Medina, right in the middle so we were able to explore upwards and hike up the mountain for incredible views as well as explore down into the main square. I couldn't quite believe it was all real, and kept feeling like I was in some sort of film set!-This was one of our highlights of our entire trip, and you guys NEED to go here when you head to Morocco! Tag everyone who would love this! Happy (not-so) blue Monday! üíôüòÇ-|| Discounted Stay ||-

üá≤üá¶ T A N N E R Y üá≤üá¶One of the main things to see in Fes is the leather tannery which is over 1000 years old. Initially I was completely put off the idea, reading reviews online but we had some spare time before we left Fes so we braved going to find it. To get the best view you have to enter one of the many leather stores that surround the tannery as they have large viewing terraces. These shops are stacked floor to ceiling with every colour of leather goods (swipe to see! üëâ)-We followed the signs on the walls (not the directions of people trying to get you lost!) and approached an alleyway of leather shops. The shop we entered had the number 14 written at the top of the doorway. The shopkeeper called us in and we made it very clear we didn't want to buy anything. He said this was fine and we could pay whatever tip we wanted to at the end. So we followed him in and we were given mint to smell to protect us from the stench.-It didn't smell as bad as I had read and it was fascinating to see these rows of over-sized painters‚Äô palettes all glistening under the Moroccan sun. The animal skins are first put in the white pots which contain a mixture of water, limestone, and pigeon droppings(!) After 2-3 days, the skins are washed and transferred to the brown pots to be coloured using cedar wood (brown), poppy flower (red), indigo (blue), henna (orange), mint (green), and saffron (yellow).-Seeing the hides and skins was confronting, especially for someone who's trying to be as vegan as possible when it comes to my food choices. It's safe to say I will never buy another leather product again but it was important to see this medieval process still being used.-Tag everyone who would be interested in this and save to your collections to keep these tips for your trip!-

üá≤üá¶ C E R A M I C S üá≤üá¶Morocco is known for its tiles, and you guys already know how obsessed I've been with the tiles around the hotels we've been staying in. I really wanted to get some handmade Moroccan ceramics and I was very aware that the stuff sold in the souks wasn't the real deal. So our tour guide @corazondemarruecos took us to a ceramic making factory in Fes called @artnaji and we watched the workers create masterpieces step by step (swipe to see!)-The clay is expertly formed into the beautiful vessels, then laid out in the sun to dry. Artists are then in the next room all sitting in a row hand-painting each piece, and then these pieces are then baked in special ovens. Tiles baked for mosaics are expertly cut into the correct shapes using chisels and hammers and then passed on to the next worker who lays the tiles out upside down to form the mosaic patterns. Which means they have to memorise the entire pattern as they can't see it until they have set the entire thing and flipped it! The final results are honestly awe-inspiring and you can buy them in the shop! The products are expensive but you're paying for quality, but still remember that the price is marked up so you need to haggle (otherwise it's a bit of a tourist trap)!-One of the most fascinating things to see, I could have stayed in their shops all day! Tag everyone who would love to see this!-

üá≤üá¶ R A I N B O W S üá≤üá¶The souks of Fes were amazing and we wish we could have explored them more, there are so many endless alleyways and turns and we were so lucky to stumble across this beautiful rainbow street!-It's notoriously hard to find so we're going to try our best to explain where it is: Go to the blue gate Bab Boujloud, take the first left, then the first right and you'll be on Rue Talaa Kebira. Walk down and keep an eye on the right, and you'll see it (the colour gets better as you walk down by the way)! It connects Rue Talaa Kebira to Rue Talaa Sghira üòç Hope that helps, save this photo to your collection to keep these instructions for later!-We absolutely loved this street and couldn't quite believe our eyes! üåà Tag everyone who would love to see this too!-

üá≤üá¶ F E S üá≤üá¶After the longest drive of our Moroccan road trip, we arrived in the city of Fes. After the serenity of the Sahara, Fes was a chaotic explosion of colour, sounds and smells, a warren of tiny alleyways that we were warned we would never find our way out of if we got lost. Slightly exhausted, we arrived at our riad @palaisamani and if you caught my stories, you would have seen how utterly blown away I was.-The little alleyways you walk down to get here are dark and narrow, and suddenly as you enter this riad, you walk onto an open courtyard with stunning trees, birds singing and grand pillars. From the outside, you have no idea that this is what is on the other side. This riad is located within the walls of the ancient Medina, but you completely forget about that once you're inside. The rooms are incredible, the staff were all so attentive, the dinner was had at their restaurant, Eden at Palais Amani, was outstanding and you can really tell that this once used to be a palace.-Swipe to see me dancing around in the grand corridors on the beautiful tiles, pretending to be a princess in her palace üòÇ What an absolute dream ‚ô•Ô∏è-Tag everyone who would love to these these pictures!-|| Complimentary Stay ||-

üá≤üá¶ S A H A R I A N N I G H T S üá≤üá¶After a day of playing in the sand dunes, we had dinner at our camp @caravanserailuxurydesertcamps as the sun set. As the stars came out (swipe to see our attempts to capture them!) and it got colder, the camp gathered around a fire and we were treated to a night of traditional Moroccan music and dance. Incredible atmosphere, right in the middle of the desert üèúÔ∏è Baj had a try at the African drums (and I cried with laughter) and then as the rest of the camp retired to their tents, we sat out on the dunes in our hoodies and watched patiently for shooting stars and saw five! üå†-It was an early start for us the following day to watch the sunrise and then start our 7 hour drive to the city of Fez with our driver @corazondemarruecos üöô Stay tuned to see what we go up to, and tag everyone who'd love these pictures and videos üòâ-|| Complimentary Stay ||-

üá≤üá¶ S A H A R A üá≤üá¶From Dades Valley, we made our way to the Sahara Desert, with our tour guide @corazondemarruecos. Our first view of the sand dunes is something I will never forget. Much like the first view of our desert camp @caravanserailuxurydesertcamps ‚õ∫ We were told by many that this was the best place to stay in the desert, and we weren't disappointed. The camp is stunning, beautifully decorated and the hospitality we received was second to none. The food was delicious, and the tent we stayed in was very comfortable, with a king sized bed and a private bathroom with running hot water!-This experience has been an absolute dream come true, playing on the sand dunes and sleeping under the stars. Thank you to @caravanserailuxurydesertcamps for making it unforgettable.-|| Complimentary Stay ||-

üá≤üá¶ G A M E OF T H R O N E S üá≤üá¶-Ait-Ben-Haddou is one of Morocco‚Äôs World Heritage Sites and it was also used as a set for Game of Thrones! But its famous for much more than being a backdrop, in the 17th century it became one of the most important ksars in the region. The outside walls of mud and clay protect the town which is built onto the side of a hill. The buildings are packed tight with narrow pathways that wind around each other and unexpectedly turn into steep staircases. At the very top is a fortress as a last line of defence.-So interesting to walk around this piece of history, listening to traditional music (see our highlighted stories for a video!) and seeing the narrow pathways lined in colour! Tag everyone who would love to see these pictures!-Travelling with @corazondemarruecos üöô-

üá≤üá¶ A R G A N O I L üá≤üá¶-After leaving Marrakech, we made our way through the Atlas mountains. We saw some incredible, panoramic views as we rode down the winding roads with our tour guide @corazondemarruecos who stopped us at the best view points (swipe to the end to see!) He then took us to a roadside shop where he told us we'd see pure Moroccan argan oil being made üòç We saw ladies cold pressing the argan seed to produce the oil which apparently retains the oil‚Äôs high Vitamin E properties and it was absolutely fascinating to see, expectedly expensive to buy, but I had to get a bottle! üôà-Tag everyone who would love to see these!-

‚ùå J A R D I N S E C R E T ‚ùå-This elegant 19th-century palace and the traditional Islamic gardens were so beautiful and we found such peace here after the chaos of the souks. This is one of the largest and most ancient palaces of the medina of Marrakech. The museum provides a wealth of historical information about Marrakech's architecture and gardens and the cafes offer fresh, homemade products üëå-A must for your Marrakech list, tag everyone who would love to see this!-

‚ùå S O U K S ‚ùå-The souks of Marrakech are the largest in Morocco and famed throughout the world as some of the most exotic marketplaces to shop in. We'd heard a lot about them before going (mainly from you guys) and we didn't really know what to expect but I can tell you now that this was one of my most favourite experiences so far. A complete maze of shadowy alleys and passages, we got completely lost in a world of multicoloured carpets, silk kaftans, spices, antiques, lanterns, pottery and jewellery. A complete sensory overload and we loved every minute of the hours we spent here.-Tag everyone who would love to see these pictures!-

B R E A K F A S T / M A R R A K E C H -Good morning from our stunning riad @safran_et_cannelle_riad_spa ‚ú® Time for some exploring with our wonderful tour guide @corazondemarruecos üöô Keep an eye on our stories for more üòç-

üá≤üá¶ M A R R A K E C H üá≤üá¶So it was an early start for us today as we drove to Gatwick for a 3 hour flight to our first destination in Morocco, the city of Marrakech. More to come on that later! We then returned to our riad and sat on the stunning rooftop and watched the sun go down üåÑ-More behind the scenes on our stories! Ever since I can remember, the Science Museum was THE place to go on a school trip and during the summer holidays, and we all looked forward to it so much! Energy company @Equinor have partnered with the Science Museum to encourage children to engage in Science, Technology, Engineering and Maths (@STEM), through the Young Imagineers Competition and being a doctor, this is something I feel strongly about and had to share!-Children aged 7-14 are being asked to come up with and invention to make tomorrow's world a better place. Maybe it's to find a solution to London's plastic waste, or to reduce the traffic on our roads, or to improve our dangerous pollution levels for future generations to have clean air? These are all topics we've campaigned about in the past!-If you think your child could enter, check out@equinor, submit a sketch and 100 words explaining the invention! Can't wait to see where this takes us! #YoungImagineers#ad-Link: https://youngimagineers.equinor.com
